# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The **1970 Women's World Cup** (Italian: **Coppa del Mondo**; sponsored name **Martini & Rossi Cup**) was an association football tournament organised by the Federation of Independent European Female Football (FIEFF) in Italy in July 1970.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] It featured women's teams from seven countries and is the first known tournament to be named as a women's football World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Matches were played in Genoa, Bologna, Milan, Bari, Salerno, Naples, and the third-place playoff and final were both in Turin.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was won by Denmark, represented by Boldklubben Femina.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Eight teams were scheduled to appear in the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The first list of participants, published in February 1970, consisted of Argentina, Denmark, France, Italy, Brazil, Czechoslovakia, England, and the Soviet Union.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] This was changed in a later revision, with West Germany, Mexico, Austria and Switzerland replacing Argentina, France, Brazil and the Soviet Union in May 1970.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Czechoslovakia would have been the only country from Europe's Eastern Bloc to compete, but the team withdrew because of visa issues.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The crowds for the tournament were "30,000-strong".
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Denmark won the tournament after beating Italy 2–0 in the final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Teams were divided into the "northern" group (in Genoa, Bologna and Milan), and "southern" (Bari, Salerno, Naples) with the top teams meeting in the final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The tournament did not involve FIFA, which had held the first men's World Cup in 1930 but did not hold any women's event until 1988.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The host country's matches are considered official by the Italian Football Federation.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The Italian women's league had been established in 1968.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Mexico, a losing semi-finalist 2–1 to Italy, were described as the "revelation" of the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Tournament memorabilia was collected at an exhibition in Pessione di Chieri (Turin) from June to August 2019.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was followed by the 1971 Women's World Cup in Mexico, and the series of five Mundialito tournaments from 1981 to 1988 in Japan and Italy, before the 1988 FIFA Women's Invitation Tournament and 1991 FIFA Women's World Cup, both in China.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The **1971 Women's World Cup** (Spanish: **1971 Campeonato de Fútbol Femenil**) was an association football tournament for women's national teams organised by the Federation of Independent European Female Football (FIEFF) in Mexico in August–September 1971.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Held in Mexico City and Guadalajara, it is the second known tournament to be named as a women's football World Cup after the 1970 edition in Italy and the first time in the same place after the men's 1970 FIFA World Cup tournament in the previous year.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] It was held twenty years before the first official FIFA women's world cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The tournament featured six national teams from Latin America and Europe, including hosts Mexico which qualified automatically.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Denmark were the tournament champions, defending its title by winning the final 3–0 against Mexico, in front of a 110,000 crowd.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] A women's football international match was played in Scotland in 1881.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Later instances included games between British, French and Belgian teams in the 1920s, and a women's European Championship in 1957.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] During this time, women's football was often stifled or banned by male-dominated football federations in many countries.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] In Brazil, women's football was effectively illegal from 1941 until 1979.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] FIEFF organised a previous Women's World Cup in Italy in 1970, also won by Denmark.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The 1971 tournament featured five different qualifying groups, four in Europe and one in the Americas, where Argentina was the only team included in the initial draw.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Italy qualified for the main tournament against England and Austria, but England was later given a place in the finals after all teams from one of the European groups (Spain, Switzerland and West Germany) withdrew from the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Similarly, France qualified by defeating the Netherlands after the withdrawal of Czechoslovakia, and Denmark qualified by default after both Belgium and Sweden withdrew.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The Americas round was not played and Argentina qualified by default, as neither potential opponents, Chile and Costa Rica, fulfilled the necessary requirements for the matches to be played.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Some of the qualifiers and finals games were officially recognised – for example, the Italian Football Federation classes all of the 1971 Italy games as full internationals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The match between France and the Netherlands in April 1971 was the first FIFA-recognised women's international match: it was played in Hazebrouck in front of 1,500 spectators.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] A protest was filled by the Dutch organization in charge of the team, to no avail.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Tournament sponsors Martini & Rossi paid for each team's travel, accommodation, and kits.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Goalposts were painted in pink hoops and stadium staff wore pink clothes, in order to try to appeal to women and families.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Ticket prices ranged from 30 pesos (£1.15) to 80 pesos (£3).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The tournament mascot was Xochitl, "a young girl in [a] football kit".
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The opening match of the finals, Mexico–Argentina (15 August) had a reported attendance of 100,000 at the Azteca Stadium.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] An estimated 80,000 people attended the Mexico–England group game.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The World Cup final, Mexico–Denmark, had an estimated attendance of 110,000, a world record for women's sport.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] This figure was reported both at the time and subsequently, and surviving footage supports the estimates.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The football record at the Azteca Stadium was three years earlier, 119,853 at the men's Mexico–Brazil match in July 1968.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The hosts Mexico qualified for the final after defeating Italy in the semifinals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Two days before the final, the Mexican press noted the players for Mexico were unhappy they had not been receiving economic support for participating in the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The Mexican team threatened to skip the final but gave up their two million peso demand and the game went forward as scheduled.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Denmark won the tournament after beating Mexico 3–0 in the final, featuring a hat trick by 15-year-old Susanne Augustesen.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The victorious Danish team were treated to a celebratory reception at Copenhagen Town Hall upon their return from the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] However, due to the unofficial nature of the tournament, it is not recognised by the Danish Football Association.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] England's team included 13-year-old Leah Caleb, 14-year-old Gill Sayell, and 15-year-old Chris Lockwood; their captain was 19-year-old Carol Wilson and they were accompanied by referee Pat Dunn as a chaperone and trainer.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] 15-year-old Susanne Augustesen scored a hat-trick for Denmark as they beat Mexico 3–0 in the final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Augustesen was honoured by the mayor of her hometown, Holbæk.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] 12 members of England's 14-woman squad reunited in June 2019 for the first time since the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] A match for fifth place was played between the two teams which did not advance to the semifinals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was later followed by the series of Mundialito tournaments throughout the 1980s, mostly held in Italy, and FIFA's Women's Invitation Tournament in China in 1988 before the first FIFA Women's World Cup in China in 1991.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] In Mexico, *Tan cerca de las nubes*, directed by Manuel Cañibe, on that country's squad that participated in the 1970 cup in Italy, as well as the 1971 one.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] In Argentina, *México 71*, directed by Carolina Gil Solari and Carolina M.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Fernández, on the Argentine squad's experiences during the cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] In the UK, *Copa 71* (2023), directed by Rachel Ramsay and James Erskine.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The **1974 FIFA World Cup** was the tenth edition of the FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for men's senior national teams, and was played in West Germany (and West Berlin) between 13 June and 7 July.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The tournament marked the first time that the current trophy, the FIFA World Cup Trophy, created by the Italian sculptor Silvio Gazzaniga, was awarded.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The previous trophy, the Jules Rimet Trophy, had been won for the third time by Brazil in 1970 and awarded permanently to the Brazilians.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] West Germany won the title, beating the Netherlands 2–1 in the final at the Olympiastadion in Munich.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] This was the second victory for West Germany, who had also won in 1954.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The teams of Australia, East Germany, Haiti and Zaire made their first appearances at the final stage, and East Germany making their only appearance before Germany was reunified in 1990.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Brazil, the defending champions, were eliminated in the second round by the Netherlands, and lost the match for third place to Poland.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Poland's Grzegorz Lato led the tournament in scoring seven goals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Gerd Müller's goal in the final was the 14th in his career of two World Cups, beating Just Fontaine's record of 13, in his single World Cup in 1958.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Müller's record was surpassed in 2006 by Ronaldo's 15 from three World Cups.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Günter Netzer, who came on as a substitute for West Germany during the defeat by the East Germans, was playing for Real Madrid at the time; this was the first time that a World Cup winner had played for a club outside his home country.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] This is the most recent of four World Cup tournaments to date with no matches needing extra time.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] West Germany was chosen as the host nation by FIFA in London, England on 6 July 1966.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Hosting rights for the 1978 and 1982 tournaments were awarded at the same time.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] West Germany agreed to a deal with Spain by which Spain would support West Germany for the 1974 tournament, and in return West Germany would allow Spain to bid for the 1982 World Cup unopposed.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Brazil went out, Pelé 'exited' through injury [following some rough defensive play], and England and Germany entered into the final, just as the Englishman Sir Stanley Rous, who was the President of FIFA at the time, had wanted.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In Germany in 1974 the same thing happened.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] During the Brazil-Netherlands match, the referee was German, we lost 2–0 and Germany won the title.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] We were the best in the world, and had the same team that had won the World Cup in 1962 in Chile and 1970 in Mexico, but it was planned for the host countries to win".
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Ninety-eight countries took part in the qualifying tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The USSR was controversially disqualified after refusing to travel for the second leg of their playoff against Chile as a result of the 1973 Chilean coup d'état.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The Netherlands and Poland qualified for the first time since 1938.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Scotland were back in the finals after a 16-year absence.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Argentina and Chile were also back after having missed the 1970 tournament and Yugoslavia returned after missing both the 1966 and 1970 tournaments.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] This was the first of eight tournaments in which the defending champions (in this case Brazil) played in the opening game rather than the hosts.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] This change was reverted for the 2006 tournament, as the defending champions no longer had a secured spot in the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] While the competition once again began with the sixteen teams divided into four groups of four teams, the eight teams which advanced did not enter a knockout stage as in the previous five World Cups but instead played in a second group stage.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The winners of the two groups in the second stage then played each other in the final, with the respective runners-up from each group meeting in the match for third place.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] This was one of only two times that this format was deployed (1978 being the other).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] For the 1974 World Cup, FIFA introduced the penalty shoot-out as a means of determining the winner in knockout stages should the match end on a draw after 120 minutes.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The method, however, was not put in practice as both the match for third place and the final were decided after 90 minutes.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The first World Cup to feature a penalty shoot-out was the 1982 World Cup, in the semi-final match between France and West Germany.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] It was decided in advance that if the host nation progressed to the second round their matches would not take place simultaneous to the other matches but instead be held in the other timeslot (either 16:00 or 19:30 local time).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The tournament was held mostly in bad weather, and the stadia had few protected places.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Only five western European nations had qualified, of which only the Netherlands, West Germany and Sweden made it past the group stage.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Fans from the Eastern Communist neighbour states East Germany, Bulgaria and Poland were hindered by political circumstances.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Carlos Caszely of Chile became the first player to be sent off with a red card in a World Cup match, during their match against West Germany.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Red cards were formally introduced in World Cup play in 1970, but no players were sent off in that tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Two teams made a particularly powerful impact on the first round.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The Netherlands demonstrated the "Total Football" techniques pioneered by the top Dutch club Ajax, in which specialised positions were virtually abolished for the outfield players, and individual players became defenders, midfielders or strikers as the situation required.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The Dutch marked their first World Cup finals since 1938 by topping their first-round group, with wins over Uruguay and Bulgaria and a draw with Sweden.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Sweden joined the Dutch in the second group round after beating Uruguay 3–0.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Poland, meanwhile, appearing for the first time since 1938, took maximum points from a group containing two of the favourites for the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] They beat Argentina 3–2, trounced Haiti 7–0, then beat Italy 2–1 – a result that allowed Argentina to qualify for the second group round ahead of Italy on goal difference.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Argentina would not fail to win either of their opening two games of a World Cup again until 2018.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] While Haiti lost all three games and finished second-to-last in the tournament, they did have one moment of glory; in their opening game against Italy, they managed to take the lead with a goal from Emmanuel Sanon, before eventually losing 3–1.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] That goal proved to be significant as it ended Dino Zoff's run of 1,142 minutes without conceding a goal – Italy had not conceded in their last 12 international matches.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] With Brazil, Yugoslavia and Scotland drawing all their games against each other, it was decided by the number of goals these three teams scored when defeating Zaire.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Yugoslavia hammered the African nation 9–0, equalling a finals record for the largest margin of victory, although the game was only played after tournament officials paid the Zaire players, after their own officials had stolen the teams wages and allowances.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Brazil beat them 3–0, which Zaire played under the threat of exile if they lost by four or more goals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Scotland only managed a 2–0 margin, and so were edged out of the tournament on goal difference.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] They were the only team that did not lose a game in the tournament and the first ever country to be eliminated from a World Cup Finals without having lost a match.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Group 1 contained both East Germany and the host West Germany, and they both progressed at the expense of Chile and newcomers Australia.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The last game played in Group 1 was much anticipated, a first ever clash between the two German teams.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] West Germany was already assured of progression to the second round whatever the result.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In one of the most politically charged matches of all time, the East won, thanks to a late Jürgen Sparwasser goal.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] This result forced a realignment of the West German team that would later help them win the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Coincidentally, the two second-round groups both produced matches that were, in effect, semi-finals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In Group A, the Netherlands and Brazil met after each had taken maximum points from their previous two matches.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In Group B, the same happened with West Germany and Poland – so the winners of these two games would contest the final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In Group A, two goals from the inspirational Johan Cruyff helped the Dutch side thrash Argentina 4–0.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] At the same time, Brazil defeated East Germany 1–0.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The Dutch triumphed over East Germany 2–0 while in the "Battle of the South Americans", Brazil managed to defeat Argentina 2–1 in a scrappy match.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Argentina and East Germany drew 1–1 and were on their way home while the crucial match between the Netherlands and Brazil turned into another triumph for Total Football, as second-half goals from Johan Neeskens and Cruyff put the Netherlands in the final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] However the match would also be remembered for harsh defending on both sides.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Meanwhile, in Group B, West Germany and Poland both managed to beat Yugoslavia and Sweden.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The crucial game between the Germans and the Poles was goalless until the 76th minute, when Gerd Muller scored to send the hosts through 1–0.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The Poles took third place after defeating Brazil 1–0.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The final was held on 7 July 1974 at Olympiastadion, Munich.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] West Germany was led by Franz Beckenbauer, while the Dutch had their star Johan Cruyff, and their Total Football system which had dazzled the competition.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] With just a minute gone on the clock, following a solo run, Cruyff was brought down by Uli Hoeneß inside the German penalty area, and the Dutch took the lead from the ensuing penalty by Johan Neeskens before any German player had even touched the ball.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] West Germany struggled to recover, and in the 26th minute were awarded a penalty, after Bernd Hölzenbein fell within the Dutch area, causing English referee Jack Taylor to award another controversial penalty.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Paul Breitner spontaneously decided to kick, and scored.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] These two penalties were the first in a World Cup final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] West Germany now pushed, and in the 43rd minute, in his typical style, Gerd Müller scored what turned out to be the winning goal, and the last of his international career as he retired from the national team.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The second half saw chances for both sides, with Müller putting the ball in the net for a goal that was disallowed as offside.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In the 85th minute, Hölzenbein was fouled again, but no penalty this time.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Eventually, West Germany, the 1972 European champions, also won the 1974 World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] This was the only case of the reigning European champions winning the World Cup, until Spain (winners of the UEFA Euro 2008) defeated the Netherlands in the 2010 FIFA World Cup final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] France have also held both trophies at the same time, albeit in a different order, by winning the 1998 FIFA World Cup followed by the UEFA Euro 2000.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] This was only the second time that a team had won the World Cup after losing a match in the finals (West Germany losing to East Germany during the group stage).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The previous occasion was West Germany's earlier win in 1954.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The official mascots of this World Cup were *Tip* and *Tap*, two boys wearing an outfit similar to West Germany's, with the letters WM (*Weltmeisterschaft*, World Cup) and number 74.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1974 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Then the remaining spots in the groups were determined by dividing the participants into pots based on geographical sections.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] When the final draw was held, the 16th and final qualifier was not yet known; it would be either Yugoslavia or Spain subject to the result of a final playoff match in February 1974.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The two teams had finished with an identical record in their qualification group, and following this situation the rules were changed, so that tied teams had to compete in a playoff match on neutral ground.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The final draw took place at 21:30 local time on 5 January 1974 in HR Sendesaal in Frankfurt, and was televised on Eurovision.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] 80 commentators were gathered at the Eurovision headquarters, and TV stations from 32 countries had requested pictures of the ceremony at the time.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The TV broadcast of this show was followed by an estimated 800 million people.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Ahead of the draw, the FIFA Organising Committee decided that the host nation (West Germany) and trophy holder (Brazil) would be seeded, and placed respectively into the first position of Groups 1 and 2 prior to the draw.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The remaining two top-seeded teams (Uruguay and Italy) would be drawn into the first position of Group 3 and Group 4.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] It was also decided that South American nations could not play in the same group during the first group stage.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In other words, Argentina and Chile drawn from pot 3, could not be drawn into the two groups seeded by Brazil and Uruguay.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay was drawn before Italy, taking the seeded first position of Group 3, and Italy were drawn into the seeded first position of Group 4.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Next, the remaining two South American teams from pot 3 were drawn into the two top-seeded European groups (Group 1 and Group 4), as per the draw regulations.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] This was followed by a draw of the remaining two European teams from pot 1 into Groups 2 and 3.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Finally other nations were drawn on an unseeded basis, one by one into Group 1–4 in numerical order, first from pot 2 and then from pot 4.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The "innocent hand" who made the draws was an 11-year-old boy, Detlef Lange, a member of the Schöneberger Sängerknaben, a children's choir.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The great sensation of the draw was the meeting of the two German teams in Group 1.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] When FIFA President Sir Stanley Rous had announced the lot, the room was quiet for a few moments, followed by long-lasting applause.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In the days following the event, a rumour began circulating that East Germany would consider withdrawing from the World Cup following a meeting with the West Germany delegation; however, this was quickly and officially denied by the East German government.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The first round, or first group stage, saw the 16 teams divided evenly into four groups.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Each group was a round-robin of six games, where each team played each of the other teams in the same group once.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Teams were awarded two points for a win, one point for a draw and none for a defeat.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The teams finishing first and second in each group qualified for the second round, while the bottom two teams in each group were eliminated from the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The second round, or second group stage, saw the eight teams progressing from the first round divided into two groups of four teams on the basis of the tournament regulations.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Group A would consist of the winners of Groups 1 and 3, plus the runners-up from Groups 2 and 4.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Group B would consist of the other four teams, namely the winners of Groups 2 and 4, plus the runners-up from Group 1 and 3.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Like the first group stage, each group in the second round was a round-robin of six games, where each team played one match against each of the other teams in the same group.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The two teams finishing first in each group advanced to the final, while the two runners-up would advance to the match for third place.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] The match for third place was the first match in FIFA World Cup history in which a penalty shoot-out could potentially be held (in the event of the score being level after the regular 90 minutes and 30 minutes' extra time).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] If the teams remained tied in the final after extra time, a replay would be held.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] Only if the scores remained level during the replay after the regular 90 minutes and 30 minutes' extra time would penalties be used to determine the champion.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] At all previous World Cup tournaments, the drawing of lots had been foreseen in this situation to split the teams, but it was never used.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] With seven goals, Grzegorz Lato of Poland was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In total, 97 goals were scored by 52 players, with two of them credited as own goals and one player scored for and against.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1974-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The **1988 FIFA Women's Invitation Tournament**, or **International Women's Football Tournament**, was organised by FIFA in China from 1 to 12 June 1988.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The competition was a test to study if a global women's World Cup was feasible following the experience of non-FIFA invitational competitions such as the Mundialito (1981–88) and the Women's World Invitational Tournament (1978–87).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The competition was a success and on 30 June FIFA approved the establishment of an official World Cup for 1991, which would also be held in China.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] Twelve national teams took part in the competition – four from UEFA, three from AFC, two from CONCACAF and one from CONMEBOL, CAF and OFC.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] European champion Norway defeated Sweden 1–0 in the final to win the tournament, while Brazil clinched the bronze by beating the hosts in a penalty shootout.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] Australia, Canada, the Netherlands and the United States also reached the final stages.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The tournament took place in 4 cities in the province of Guangdong: Guangzhou, Foshan, Jiangmen and Panyu.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] 12 national teams participated in the tournament, all invited by FIFA.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The matches of China were held in Guangzhou.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The rest of the matches of this group were held in Foshan.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The all star team was voted by the Chinese press.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] The **1991 FIFA Women's World Cup final** was an association football match that took place on 30 November 1991 at Tianhe Stadium in Guangzhou, China.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] It was played between Norway and the United States to determine the winner of the 1991 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] The United States beat Norway 2–1, with two goals from Michelle Akers-Stahl, to become winners of the first ever FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] The final was contested by Norway, who rebounded from a stunning 4–0 defeat by host nation China PR to qualify from their group.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] They then dispatched Italy and historic rivals Sweden in the knockout rounds to reach the final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] The other team in the final was the United States, who went undefeated throughout the competition, thrashing highly rated Germany 5–2 in the semi-final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The **1991 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification** process saw 48 teams from the six FIFA confederations compete for the 12 places in the 1991 FIFA Women's World Cup finals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] All of the confederations used their regional championship tournament to determine qualification.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] Hosts China PR also entered the qualifying process.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The qualification process spanned nearly two years, beginning with the first match on 9 September 1989 and the qualification concluded on 14 July 1991.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] A total of 445 goals were scored in the 111 qualifying matches (an average of 4.01 per match).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] Four teams withdrew during the qualification without playing a match: Congo, Senegal, Zambia, and Zimbabwe, all of which are African teams.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The only African team to qualify to the World Cup was the winner of the 1991 African Women's Championship, Nigeria.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The eight teams were paired together into two knockout ties.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The winners of these ties advanced to the second round, who used the same format as the first round.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The final round is a two-leg final between the two winners of the second round.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The winner, Nigeria qualified to the World Cup and won the tournament by defeating Cameroon 6–0 on aggregate.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The 1991 AFC Women's Championship, consisting of nine teams, served as the AFC's qualifying tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The first round was composed of two groups, one of four teams and the other of five.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The top two teams of the groups advanced to the semi-finals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] In the semi-finals, the winners advanced to the final and the losers played the third-place match.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The winner, China; runners-up, Japan; and third place, Chinese Taipei, qualified to the World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The first official edition of the UEFA Women's Championship served also as UEFA's qualifying tournament for the World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] Out of the 18 teams participating in the tournament, the qualifiers were the four semi-finalists—Denmark, Germany, Italy, and Norway—and the best quarter-final loser, Sweden, who lost their two-leg quarter-final clash against Italy on a single away goal.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The UEFA Women's Championship had held its own qualifying campaign.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] It began in September 1989, and ended with a final four–style tournament in Denmark, held in July 1991, only four months before the World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] Germany won the tournament by beating Norway 3–1 in extra time.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The 1991 CONCACAF's Women's Championship, despite being an unofficial competition, determined the CONCACAF's single qualifier for the World Cup – the winner, the United States.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The tournament took place in Port-au-Prince, Haiti in April 1991 and consisted of 8 teams.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] Only three teams participated in the tournament which took place in Sydney, Australia in May 1991: Australia, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The teams played in a round-robin tournament in which each team played 2 matches against each opponent, with the first placed team qualifying.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The competition was eventually decided through goal-difference, as the matches between Australia and New Zealand ended with one win to each side, and both teams won all matches against Papua New Guinea.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The first edition of the Sudamericano Femenino (Women's South American Championship), held in April–May 1991 determined CONMEBOL's qualifier.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-qualification] The host of the tournament Brazil won the tournament and with it the right to represent South America in the World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The **1991 FIFA Women's World Cup** was the first FIFA Women's World Cup, the world championship for women's national football teams.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It took place in Guangdong, China from 16 to 30 November 1991.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA, football's international governing body, selected China as host nation as Guangdong had hosted a prototype world championship three years earlier, the 1988 FIFA Women's Invitation Tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Matches were played in the provincial capital, Guangzhou, as well as in Foshan, Jiangmen and Zhongshan.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The competition was sponsored by Mars, Incorporated, maker of M&M's candy.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] With FIFA still reluctant to bestow their "World Cup" brand, the tournament was officially known as the **1st FIFA World Championship for Women's Football for the M&M's Cup**.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It was won by the United States, whose captain April Heinrichs formed a forward line dubbed the "Triple-Edged Sword" with Carin Jennings and Michelle Akers.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Jennings was named player of the tournament while Akers's ten goals won the Golden Boot.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The United States defeated Norway 2–1 in the final in front of a crowd of 63,000 people at Guangzhou's Tianhe Stadium.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Total attendance for the tournament was 510,000, an average per match of 19,615.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the opening match at the same stadium, Norway was defeated 4–0 by hosts China.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Chinese defender Ma Li scored the first goal in Women's World Cup history, while goalkeeper Zhong Honglian, also of China, posted the first official clean sheet in the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The 12 qualified teams were divided into three groups of four (A to C).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The top two teams and the two best third-place finishers from the three groups advanced to the knockout round of eight teams.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For only this first edition of the Women's World Cup, all matches lasted only 80 minutes, instead of the typical 90, and two points were awarded for a win (both of which would change in 1995).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The 1991 Women's World Cup had twelve participating teams compete in the final tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each of the six FIFA confederations had at least one representative.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For a list of the squads that contended for the final tournament, see *1991 FIFA Women's World Cup squads*.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For the first time in FIFA competition, six female officials were included.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] All functioned as lineswomen, except for Cláudia Vasconcelos who took charge of the third place play-off; becoming the first woman to referee a match sanctioned by FIFA.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA's technical report demonstrates that, after the tournament, players and officials were undecided whether to persist with 80-minute matches, or to change to 90 minutes in line with men's football.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Opinion was also divided about the suitability of using a size five football.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Some teams reported difficulty in sourcing good quality equipment in the correct size.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was considered a major success in the quality of play and attendances at the games.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The perceived success of the tournament was a significant factor in the subsequent inclusion of women's football in the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Sue Lopez reported that although attendances were very high, many tickets were complimentary.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The "novelty factor" of women from foreign lands playing football also encouraged local people to attend.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The draw for the group stage was held on 14 September 1991 at the Tianhe Stadium in Guangzhou, China.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The draw was part of a televised two-hour live show, featuring songs in both Chinese and English from the female singers Zhang Qiang (Beijing), Lin Ping (Guangzhou), Jenny Tseng (Hong Kong) and Irene Yeh (Taiwan).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Rules for classification: 1) Points; 2) Goal difference; 3) Goals scored.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] There were 99 goals scored in 26 matches, for an average of 3.81 goals per match.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Michelle Akers-Stahl of the United States won the Golden Boot award for scoring ten goals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Per statistical convention in football, matches decided in extra time are counted as wins and losses, while matches decided by penalty shoot-outs are counted as draws.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The **2011 FIFA Women's World Cup** was the sixth FIFA Women's World Cup competition, the world championship for women's national football teams.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It was held from 26 June to 17 July 2011 in Germany, which won the right to host the event in October 2007.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Japan won the final against the United States on a penalty shoot-out following a 2–2 draw after extra time and became the first Asian team to win a senior FIFA World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The matches were played in nine stadiums in nine host cities around the country, with the final played at the Commerzbank Arena in Frankfurt.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Sixteen teams were selected for participation via a worldwide qualification tournament that began in 2009.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the first round of the tournament finals, the teams competed in round-robin groups of four teams for points, with the top two teams in each group proceeding.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] These eight teams advanced to the knockout stage, where two rounds of play decided which teams would participate in the final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The hosts and defending champions Germany were eliminated by Japan in the quarterfinals with a 1-0 result in extra time.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Six nations, Australia, Canada, France, Germany, Peru and Switzerland, initially declared their interest in hosting the 2011 Women's World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The German Football Association announced its hopes to host the tournament on 26 January 2006, following a pledge from German Chancellor Angela Merkel to fully support a potential bid.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] All six nations officially announced their interest by a 1 March 2007 deadline and acknowledged their intention of bidding by 3 May 2007 to FIFA.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The final bidding dossiers had to be handed over before 1 August 2007.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Switzerland withdrew on 29 May 2007, stating that Europe is heavily focused on France and Germany, and a third European bid appeared futile.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 27 August 2007, France also withdrew, reportedly in exchange for Germany's support for their bid to host the men's UEFA Euro 2016.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Later Australia (12 October 2007) and Peru (17 October 2007) voluntarily dropped out of the race as well, leaving only Canada and Germany as the remaining candidates.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 30 October 2007, the FIFA Executive Committee voted to assign the tournament to Germany.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Canada was eventually awarded the 2015 Women's World Cup four years later.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Upon the selection, Germany became the third country to host both men's and women's World Cup, having hosted the men's twice in 1974 and 2006.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] After the German Football Association (DFB) expressed its intention to bid for the Women's World Cup, 23 German cities applied to host World Cup games.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Twelve cities were chosen for the official bidding dossier handed over to FIFA in August 2007.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 30 September 2008, the DFB executive committee decided to use nine stadiums for the tournament; the original candidates Essen, Magdeburg and Bielefeld were not chosen as World Cup venues.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The official opening game was held between Germany and Canada at the Olympic Stadium in Berlin, the venue of the 2006 men's World Cup final; it was the only match played in Berlin.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] However, it was not the first match of the tournament—it was preceded by a match at Rhein-Neckar-Arena in Sinsheim pitting France and Nigeria.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The final of the tournament took place at the Commerzbank-Arena in Frankfurt, the venue of the 2005 men's Confederations Cup final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Borussia-Park in Mönchengladbach and Frankfurt's Commerzbank-Arena hosted the semi-finals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The third place play-off was held at Rhein-Neckar-Arena.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Since 2007, five of the stadiums were either newly built (Augsburg, Dresden and Sinsheim) or remodelled (Bochum and Leverkusen).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Six stadiums would be home grounds for German First Bundesliga clubs in the upcoming 2011–12 season, while the other three would be home to Second Bundesliga clubs in the same season.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Compared to the 2006 men's World Cup, several smaller venues were chosen; six stadiums have a capacity of 20,000 to 30,000 seats.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] All cities would stage a total of four matches, with the exceptions of Berlin and Mönchengladbach; the latter would host three games.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The total capacity of the nine venues is roughly 330,000.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Overall, approximately one million tickets would be available.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Several of the stadiums were officially referred to simply as "FIFA Women's World Cup Stadium" because FIFA prohibited sponsorship of stadiums unless the stadium sponsors were also official tournament sponsors.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] With no standing-room terraces allowed, all stadiums had a lower total capacity compared to German Bundesliga games.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA had considered the prospect of increasing the number of teams from 16 to 24, to reflect the growing global popularity of women's football and the Women's World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] However, on 14 March 2008, the FIFA Executive Committee decided to keep the number of participants at 16, concerned that more teams would dilute the quality of play.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The idea of having 20 teams taking part, which had been discussed briefly, was ruled impossible to implement in terms of fixture planning and logistics.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] During the 2007 Women's World Cup, FIFA president Sepp Blatter had campaigned for the idea to increase the number of teams, although this proposal was not unquestioned.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In particular the 11–0 victory of Germany over Argentina in the opening game of the 2007 tournament had caused a debate over whether there were 24 national teams on a comparable level.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In October 2008, the FIFA Executive Committee announced a change to the allocation of the qualifying berths for its continental confederations.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Asia was granted 3 automatic berths instead of 2.5 for the finals (although in 2007 the host nation was an additional qualifier from Asia).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Europe's allocation was reduced from 5 to 4.5 (although it effectively increased to 5.5 because of the automatic qualification of the host nation).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The North/Central American and Caribbean confederation (CONCACAF) retained their 2.5 qualifiers, Africa and South America 2 each, and Oceania 1.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The 16th qualifying spot was determined through a play-off between the third-placed team in CONCACAF and the winner of repechage play-offs in Europe.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA also ruled that each confederation has to ensure that at least one third of its member associations enter their women's national teams for World Cup qualification, otherwise FIFA would re-examine the current slot allocation.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In Africa and the Middle East a considerable percentage of teams had withdrawn from World Cup qualification in the past.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For European teams, the 2011 Women's World Cup was also used as a qualification tournament for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Besides Team Great Britain, Europe had two additional qualifiers for the Summer Olympics.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] With Germany losing their quarter-final, France, which had already reached the semi-finals, secured qualification to the Olympics.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Sweden followed as UEFA's second team with its win against Australia.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Qualification for the tournament took place between April 2009 and November 2010.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] As the host nation, Germany were granted automatic qualification, while the remaining national teams qualified through their continental confederations.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Most confederations used their continental championship tournaments – the AFC Women's Asian Cup, CAF Women's Championship, OFC Women's Championship, Sudamericano Femenino and CONCACAF Women's Gold Cup – to determine qualification.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The exception to this was UEFA, which used its own qualifying tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] One qualification spot was determined by a play-off between a UEFA and CONCACAF team.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Colombia and Equatorial Guinea made their debuts in the FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Brazil, Germany, Japan, Nigeria, Norway, Sweden and the United States maintained their streak of qualifying for all six tournaments so far, while China PR failed to qualify for the first time ever.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] This is Mexico's first appearance since 1999 and France's first appearance since 2003.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament is supervised by the "Women's World Cup 2011 Organising Committee Germany".
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] President of the Organising Committee (OC) is former German international Steffi Jones; she started her work on 1 January 2008.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] German president Christian Wulff was named the patron of the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The Organising Committee is chaired by Jones and supervised by the board of the German Football Federation (DFB).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 25 January 2009, Jones opened the committee offices and named her OC team.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It is led by managing director Uli Wolter, who headed the Leipzig branch during the 2006 men's World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Aside from Wolter, four department heads were named.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Intended to advertise the tournament primarily in Germany, the Organising Committee named four national Women's World Cup ambassadors: former German internationals Britta Carlson, Renate Lingor, and Sandra Minnert, as well as shooting Paralympics gold medallist Manuela Schmermund.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In October 2009, former U.S. international Mia Hamm was presented as the World Cup's international ambassador.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each host city except for Berlin also named two city ambassadors.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] They include footballers Matthias Sammer, Karl-Heinz Riedle and Rainer Bonhof, fencer Britta Heidemann or biathlete Magdalena Neuner.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The official World Cup emblem, called Arena Deutschland, was presented by Steffi Jones and Franz Beckenbauer in the break between the women's and the men's game of the German Cup final on 19 April 2008.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It shows a stylised stadium with stripes in the national colours of Germany, black, red and gold, and a pictogram of the Women's World Cup trophy in the upper right corner.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It was designed by the Stuttgart advertising agency WVP.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament mascot, cat "Karla Kick", was presented during the opening game of the 2010 Under-20 Women's World Cup on 13 July 2010.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The mascot was developed by the Frankfurt agency GMR Marketing.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] According to Jones, the mascot represents "important attributes of women's football: passion, fun and dynamics".
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Approximately one million tickets were available in total, with 900,000 on general sale.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] 350,000 tickets were offered at discount prices, mainly intended for families, clubs and schools, one of the key target groups of the Organising Committee.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The World Cup tickets were offered in several sales phases.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] During the first sales period from 29 October 2009 to 31 August 2010, only so-called city series tickets were offered.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each city series includes tickets for all games of that particular host city.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the second sales period from 17 February to 31 August 2010, so-called 20Eleven tickets were sold to groups of at least 11 people, offered at a 20 percent discount and directed primarily at schools and clubs.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Single tickets for all matches were first sold starting 15 September 2010.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The prices of individual tickets range from €10 to €200.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 18 March 2011, 100 days before the opening game, the last sales phase started, with all remaining tickets being sold in the order in which orders are received.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Unlike tickets at the 2006 men's World Cup in Germany, the tickets for the Women's World Cup were not personalised.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The same city series ticket can be used by different people for different games.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament's budget has been set at €51 million.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The German Football Association plans to cover these costs in almost equal parts from ticket sales and from sponsors, primarily from six so-called National Supporters.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In order for the tournament to break even, the DFB has said about 80% of the tickets need to be sold, which would translate to an average attendance of 25,000.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The DFB estimates to earn roughly €27 million through the general ticket sale.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] From 2008 to 2010, the six National Supporters were presented: the tele-communications company Deutsche Telekom, the bank Commerzbank, the insurer Allianz, the retailer Rewe, the national mail company Deutsche Post and the national railway company Deutsche Bahn.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Aside from Deutsche Bahn, the sponsors are identical with those of the 2010 U-20 Women's World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The television coverage of the tournament was unprecedented.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For the first time, all matches were produced in high definition, with in-goal cameras and two steadicams being used for all matches.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For selected matches, the broadcast production comprised up to 18 cameras, including a spidercam and a helicopter camera.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In Germany the public broadcasters ARD and ZDF showed all 32 tournament games live.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Across Europe, all games were available on Eurosport in 34 countries and territories.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the United States, ESPN and ESPN2 served as the official English-language broadcaster, while Univision carried coverage in Spanish.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In Canada, CBC Television and Sportsnet broadcast the tournament; the event was the first in a sub-licensing partnership for FIFA tournaments between the two networks.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the United Kingdom, the games of the England national team were shown live by BBC Red Button and the BBC Sport website.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] SBS held the broadcasting rights for Australia, while Al Jazeera broadcast matches in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was the first women's event to be the subject of a Panini sticker album, available only in Germany.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The final match between Japan and the United States broke the record for most tweets per second on Twitter – 7,196.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA's Referees' Committee selected 16 referees to officiate at the World Cup: three from the AFC, one from the CAF, two from CONMEBOL, three from CONCACAF, one from the OFC and six from UEFA.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In addition 32 assistant referees and three fourth officials were selected.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The oldest referee was 42-year-old Swede Jenny Palmquist, while the youngest referee was 29-year-old Finau Vulvuli of Fiji.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] As with the 2007 tournament, each team's squad for the 2011 Women's World Cup consisted of 21 players, two less than men's World Cup squads.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each participating national association had to confirm their final 21-player squad no later than 10 working days before the start of the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Replacement of seriously injured players was permitted until 24 hours before the team in question's first World Cup game.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 25 June 2011 the A sample of Yineth Varón, goalkeeper of Colombia, tested positive to an as yet unknown substance.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] She was provisionally suspended by the FIFA until the B sample result was known.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 25 August 2011, it was confirmed that she had received a two-year ban.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 7 July 2011, FIFA announced that two players from North Korea, Song Jong-Sun and Jong Pok-Sim, were provisionally suspended prior to their team's match against Colombia after failing doping tests during the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 16 July, FIFA announced that three additional players (Hong Myong-Hui, Ho Un-Byol and Ri Un-Hyang) from North Korea tested positive following target testing of the whole team.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] On 25 August 2011, the Korean team was fined US$400,000, which is equal to the prize it received by finishing 13th in the 2011 tournament, and was excluded from participation at the 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The Organising Committee approved the procedure for the final draw on 28 November 2010.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Four teams from different geographic regions – Germany, Japan, United States, Brazil – were seeded based on their FIFA Women's World Rankings.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] No two teams from the same confederation were to be drawn in the same group, with the exception of Group A, which would include two European teams.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The group draw was staged in Frankfurt, Germany, on 29 November 2010 at the Congress Centrum.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The ceremony was presented by Organising Committee president Steffi Jones, assisted by FIFA Head of Women's Competitions Tatjana Haenni.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The balls were drawn by former German international Günter Netzer and Slovak model and women's football ambassador Adriana Karembeu.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Group A was the group of death of this FIFA World Cup with three top 10-ranked teams: Germany (2), Canada (6) and France (7).
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The first round, or group stage, sees the sixteen teams divided into four groups of four teams.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each group is a round-robin of six games, where each team plays one match against each of the other teams in the same group.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Teams are awarded three points for a win, one point for a draw and none for a defeat.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The teams finishing first and second in each group qualifies for the quarter-finals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The match schedule for the tournament was released on 20 March 2009, with the hosts placed in position A1.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Unlike previous Women's World Cup final tournaments, there were no double-headers, but matches on the same day were held in different venues.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] According to the Organising Committee, this "signals the increased quality and status of the women's finals".
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The knockout stage comprised the eight teams that advanced from the group stage of the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] There were three rounds of matches, with each round eliminating half of the teams entering that round.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The successive rounds were the quarter-finals, semi-finals, and the final.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] There is also a play-off to decide third and fourth place.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For each game in the knockout stage, any draw at 90 minutes was followed by thirty minutes of extra time; if scores were still level, there would be a penalty shootout to determine who progressed to the next round.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The following awards were given at the conclusion of the tournament.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The Golden Ball (best overall player), Golden Boot (top scorer) and Golden Glove (best goalkeeper) awards were sponsored by Adidas, while the Best Young Player award was sponsored by Hyundai Motor Company.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA.com shortlisted ten goals for users to vote on as the Goal of the Tournament, which was sponsored by Sony.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] There were 86 goals scored in 32 matches, for an average of 2.69 goals per match.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Homare Sawa of Japan won the Golden Boot award for scoring five goals.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Aya Miyama of Japan won the assists table with four assists.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In June 2023, Nilla Fischer revealed in her book, *I Didn't Even Say Half Of It*, that the Swedish team were told to show their genitalia to prove that they were women during the 2011 competition.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] This came after protests from Nigeria, South Africa and Ghana relating to allegations that the Equatorial Guinea squad included men.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Fischer described the process, which was conducted by a female physiotherapist on behalf of the doctor, as humiliating but did not have a choice in order to not jeopardise the opportunity to play at a World Cup.
[src:2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2011-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA said it had taken note of recent comments made by Nilla Fischer around her experiences and gender verification testing conducted by the Swedish national team at the World Cup.
